               <p>JONATHAN BAKER sworn. - I am a <rs id="t18010916-87-viclabel451" type="occupation">pawnbroker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18010916-87-victim607 t18010916-87-viclabel451"></join> in <placeName id="t18010916-87-crimeloc452">Brick-lane, Whitechapel</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18010916-87-crimeloc452" type="placeName" value="Brick-lane, Whitechapel"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18010916-87-crimeloc452" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18010916-87-off449 t18010916-87-crimeloc452"></join>; the prisoner, on the 12th of September, with another woman, came into my shop and asked the prices of various articles, particularly of this cloak, which was hanging at the door; immediately upon their dispersing from the shop I missed the cloak; I went into the street and saw the prisoner go into a public-house; she called for a pint of beer; I desired her to let me see what she had under her cloak; I moved her cloak on one side, and there I found this cloak under her arm; she offered to pay me for it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's defence. I went with another woman; I came out of the shop because my child was crying; she came out and gave me the cloak, and told me she had bought it, and desired me to go into the public-house and call for a pint of beer.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18010916-87-verdict453" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18010916-87-verdict453" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>First Middlesex Jury, before Mr. Common Serjeant.</p>
